1
00:00:20,487 --> 00:00:23,088
PORTIA:  <i>An admissions</i>
<i>officer must have</i>
<i>a strong constitution</i>

2
00:00:23,090 --> 00:00:24,523
<i>to be on the receiving end</i>

3
00:00:24,525 --> 00:00:27,559
<i>of an entire nation's</i>
<i>application panic,</i>

4
00:00:27,561 --> 00:00:29,661
<i>to endure</i>
<i>the frustration and anger</i>

5
00:00:29,663 --> 00:00:32,331
<i>of all the so-called</i>
<i>millennial parents</i>

6
00:00:32,333 --> 00:00:33,632
<i>who just realized...</i>

7
00:00:33,634 --> 00:00:34,800
Come on, hurry up!

8
00:00:34,802 --> 00:00:38,337
PORTIA:  <i>...there isn't room</i>
<i>for every perfectly nurtured,</i>

9
00:00:38,339 --> 00:00:41,273
<i>organically fed,</i>
<i>well-tutored offspring.</i>

10
00:00:41,275 --> 00:00:42,408
Okay, I'm your tour guide.

11
00:00:42,410 --> 00:00:44,109
There's no point
trying to impress me.

12
00:00:44,111 --> 00:00:47,613
I have absolutely
no power over
your fate here.

13
00:00:47,615 --> 00:00:49,314
The people
with the power
are right in there.

14
00:00:49,316 --> 00:00:50,482
The admissions officers.

15
00:00:52,352 --> 00:00:54,453
And, no, that sign
is not an omen.

16
00:00:54,455 --> 00:00:58,690
Except for some of you.
Almost all of you, actually.

17
00:00:58,692 --> 00:01:03,495
We had 26,241
applications last year,

18
00:01:03,497 --> 00:01:06,231
1,308 of those applicants

19
00:01:06,233 --> 00:01:07,366
are attending school here.
(DOOR OPENS)

20
00:01:08,435 --> 00:01:09,435
(ALL GASP)

21
00:01:15,508 --> 00:01:18,444
James,
tours leave at 9:15.
It's 9:25.

22
00:01:18,446 --> 00:01:22,181
Sorry. I thought I'd wait.
We had a, uh, late arrival.

23
00:01:22,183 --> 00:01:24,516
I'm sorry. Our GPS lied.

24
00:01:26,519 --> 00:01:29,555
No worries, Mrs. Lafont.

25
00:01:30,623 --> 00:01:32,424
Welcome to Princeton.

26
00:01:34,527 --> 00:01:35,861
So what's
the secret to getting in?

27
00:01:36,529 --> 00:01:37,396
The secret...

28
00:01:42,135 --> 00:01:43,368
Just be yourself.

29
00:01:43,370 --> 00:01:45,504
If this is
the right place for you,

30
00:01:45,506 --> 00:01:47,439
then this is
where you'll end up.

31
00:01:48,708 --> 00:01:50,476
James?

32
00:01:50,478 --> 00:01:52,444
Okay, let's go see Princeton!
We're going to play
a fun game.

33
00:01:52,446 --> 00:01:54,813
It's called "Spot
the Nobel Prize Winner."

34
00:01:54,815 --> 00:01:57,816
PORTIA:  <i>What's</i>
<i>the secret to getting in?</i>
<i>There has to be one, right?</i>

35
00:01:57,818 --> 00:02:01,286
<i>Well, there is,</i>
<i>but I can't tell you.</i>
<i>Not yet.</i>

36
00:02:01,288 --> 00:02:03,856
<i>What I can tell you</i>
<i>is everyone</i>
<i>thinks we're sadists.</i>

37
00:02:03,858 --> 00:02:07,192
<i>That we like saying no.</i>
<i>This is not true.</i>

38
00:02:07,194 --> 00:02:08,527
<i>No.</i>
<i>Portia.</i>

39
00:02:08,529 --> 00:02:12,297
You're second reader
on my territory this season.

40
00:02:12,299 --> 00:02:15,300
Yes, I know.
As are you. On mine.
That's the way it works.

41
00:02:15,302 --> 00:02:16,468
(LAUGHS)

42
00:02:18,705 --> 00:02:22,407
Oh, I'll just wait until
you catch up. With me.

43
00:02:22,409 --> 00:02:23,775
(PHONE RINGING)

44
00:02:23,777 --> 00:02:27,379
PORTIA:  <i>We are</i>
<i>in this job</i>
<i>for one reason.</i>

45
00:02:27,381 --> 00:02:28,380
Hello?
JOHN:  <i>Is this Portia Nathan?</i>

46
00:02:28,382 --> 00:02:29,681
PORTIA:  <i>To say...</i>
<i>Yes?</i>

47
00:02:29,683 --> 00:02:30,916
Wow, I didn't
think I'd get you.

48
00:02:30,918 --> 00:02:32,551
It's John Pressman

49
00:02:32,553 --> 00:02:34,620
from The New Quest School
in Keene, New Hampshire.

50
00:02:34,622 --> 00:02:38,557
Yeah.
I sent you a few e-mails,
and left a couple of messages.

51
00:02:38,559 --> 00:02:41,226
Can you please
e-mail me
your information

52
00:02:41,228 --> 00:02:42,361
and I will call you back?

53
00:02:42,363 --> 00:02:43,428
Hey, not so rough.
How'd you like

54
00:02:43,430 --> 00:02:44,530
to have your udder
yanked like that?

55
00:02:44,532 --> 00:02:47,299
Sorry, I was just
talking to a student.
Uh.

56
00:02:47,301 --> 00:02:49,501
CLARENCE: People!
Everyone, please.

57
00:02:50,303 --> 00:02:52,471
I have a couple
of announcements.

58
00:02:52,473 --> 00:02:54,406
There is an announcement.

59
00:02:54,408 --> 00:02:56,175
Portia, we're a new
developmental school,

60
00:02:56,177 --> 00:02:58,610
and we have
our first graduating
class this year.

61
00:02:58,612 --> 00:03:00,746
I know you're gonna
be making your school visits
in the next few weeks.

62
00:03:00,748 --> 00:03:05,684
<i>Our kids would</i>
<i>gain a lot from it,</i>
<i>and I think you would, too.</i>

63
00:03:05,686 --> 00:03:07,553
Right,
I will look into it.
I got to go.

64
00:03:07,555 --> 00:03:09,321
I went to Dartmouth,
same time as you...

65
00:03:09,323 --> 00:03:12,291
Bye.
Thank you for calling.

66
00:03:12,293 --> 00:03:15,794
So, we're breaking records
in application numbers,
naturally,

67
00:03:15,796 --> 00:03:19,364
because we've been
number one for so long.

68
00:03:19,366 --> 00:03:21,600
Number one until today.

69
00:03:23,269 --> 00:03:25,404
Princeton
has just fallen
to number two.

70
00:03:28,341 --> 00:03:32,477
What this means
is that we all have
to work harder than ever.

71
00:03:32,479 --> 00:03:34,346
Because I want
to go out on top.

72
00:03:34,348 --> 00:03:36,615
Yes, you see,
the rumors are true.

73
00:03:37,650 --> 00:03:38,850
I have decided
to retire

74
00:03:38,852 --> 00:03:43,555
and pass the baton
to a worthy successor.

75
00:03:43,557 --> 00:03:44,890
I'm spending
an extra four days

76
00:03:44,892 --> 00:03:46,358
in the Andover
Hotchkiss triangle.

77
00:03:46,360 --> 00:03:47,693
And I've added
five full days

78
00:03:47,695 --> 00:03:49,995
to the San Francisco
Bay Area
in Northern California.

79
00:03:49,997 --> 00:03:52,497
And I've added
a number of new schools.

80
00:03:52,499 --> 00:03:55,968
In fact, I was just talking
to the co-founder of Quest,

81
00:03:55,970 --> 00:03:59,004
a developmental high school
with their first year
of college applicants.

82
00:03:59,006 --> 00:04:00,906
Clarence,
we're going
to be back on top.

83
00:04:00,908 --> 00:04:02,975
We're going to
make that happen
by working together.

84
00:04:02,977 --> 00:04:04,676
Right, Portia?

85
00:04:05,678 --> 00:04:07,346
Absolutely.

86
00:04:07,348 --> 00:04:09,881
As a mother myself,
I know the importance
of teamwork.

87
00:04:09,883 --> 00:04:11,617
And I'm not a mother,

88
00:04:11,619 --> 00:04:13,485
but I know
the importance of it, too.

89
00:04:13,487 --> 00:04:14,953
Can't go it alone.

90
00:04:16,923 --> 00:04:18,924
CLARENCE: Good.

91
00:04:18,926 --> 00:04:21,827
Because you two
are my superstars.

92
00:04:21,829 --> 00:04:24,263
And nothing
would make me happier

93
00:04:24,265 --> 00:04:28,333
than if one of you
were to have this
office next year.

94
00:04:29,502 --> 00:04:31,303
(SNIPPING)

95
00:04:39,879 --> 00:04:41,813
Okay.

96
00:04:41,815 --> 00:04:43,715
Class of 2016.

97
00:04:47,320 --> 00:04:49,921
Pediatric surgery
best combines
my love of children,

98
00:04:49,923 --> 00:04:51,390
of science,

99
00:04:51,392 --> 00:04:53,925
and my desire
to give back
to my community.

100
00:04:53,927 --> 00:04:56,595
Yes, but you
didn't challenge
yourself academically.

101
00:04:56,597 --> 00:04:59,698
B's in physics
and you didn't
take AP Chem.

102
00:05:03,671 --> 00:05:09,308
Since 1841,
every male in my family
has attended the place.

103
00:05:11,811 --> 00:05:14,613
Student body president
and gymnastics
national champion.

104
00:05:14,615 --> 00:05:18,750
Educated family.
Privileged upbringing.
Unfair advantage?

105
00:05:18,752 --> 00:05:22,321
Twenty-four hundred
on the SAT. 4.5 GPA.

106
00:05:22,323 --> 00:05:24,723
And my poetry,
written in my
mother's psych ward,

107
00:05:24,725 --> 00:05:26,058
will be published by Knopf.

108
00:05:26,060 --> 00:05:28,327
And my father is Cuban.

109
00:05:28,329 --> 00:05:29,628
And in a wheelchair.

110
00:05:31,531 --> 00:05:32,664
(KNOCKING ON DOOR)

111
00:05:33,533 --> 00:05:34,800
Hey, can I get
some advice?

112
00:05:34,802 --> 00:05:37,636
No. Applicatus interruptus.
You know the rule.

113
00:05:37,638 --> 00:05:39,471
Never start a folder
if you can't finish it.

114
00:05:40,373 --> 00:05:42,441
(SIGHS)

115
00:05:42,443 --> 00:05:43,909
I have to start
over anyway. Okay.

116
00:05:43,911 --> 00:05:47,346
This kid from Alaska,
Aput Kunayak. Uh...

117
00:05:47,348 --> 00:05:49,881
High grades,
but low scores.

118
00:05:49,883 --> 00:05:53,051
President of 10 clubs,
but that might be
because of his ADD.

119
00:05:53,053 --> 00:05:56,054
We want to accept people
who will succeed here.

120
00:05:56,056 --> 00:05:59,691
I once fought
for a bipolar Inuit girl,
and she lasted 19 days.

121
00:06:00,493 --> 00:06:01,393
Do you think he might fail?

122
00:06:01,395 --> 00:06:03,028
Maybe. I like him.

123
00:06:06,132 --> 00:06:08,700
It's so hard.

124
00:06:08,702 --> 00:06:13,438
You have to toughen up
or you won't last here either.

125
00:06:13,440 --> 00:06:14,740
Now outsies.
I'm swamped.

126
00:06:16,542 --> 00:06:18,043
Portia?

127
00:06:18,045 --> 00:06:18,977
I hope it's you.

128
00:06:19,612 --> 00:06:20,712
Thank you.

129
00:06:21,748 --> 00:06:22,848
Back to work.

130
00:06:27,387 --> 00:06:28,820
(SOFT MUSIC PLAYING)

131
00:06:34,694 --> 00:06:35,794
(DOOR BELL RINGING)

132
00:06:35,796 --> 00:06:36,795
RACHAEL: Portia?

133
00:06:37,063 --> 00:06:38,130
Hello?

134
00:06:38,132 --> 00:06:40,532
Portia? Portia. Portia.

135
00:06:40,534 --> 00:06:42,667
I'm so sorry.
I've got an emergency.

136
00:06:42,669 --> 00:06:44,970
Can you just
watch the kids
while I run to the vet?

137
00:06:44,972 --> 00:06:47,038
Because Richard's at
his Faulkner seminar.

138
00:06:47,040 --> 00:06:50,008
Me? Mark should
have been home
20 minutes ago.

139
00:06:50,010 --> 00:06:52,144
And it's our poetry night.

140
00:06:52,146 --> 00:06:55,080
And, really,
I'm the last person you want
watching your kids.

141
00:06:55,082 --> 00:06:56,882
(KIDS CRYING)

142
00:07:00,987 --> 00:07:02,087
Quiet.

143
00:07:03,022 --> 00:07:04,556
Did someone die?

144
00:07:04,558 --> 00:07:06,825
Rachael's dog's sick.
She begged me.

145
00:07:07,760 --> 00:07:09,161
Good times.

146
00:07:09,163 --> 00:07:10,762
(CHILDREN CRYING)

147
00:07:11,664 --> 00:07:13,198
I've got essays to grade.

148
00:07:16,903 --> 00:07:18,136
(CRYING STOPS)

149
00:07:18,138 --> 00:07:20,005
Oh, it's okay.

150
00:07:20,007 --> 00:07:22,507
Aw, it's okay. Mommy's here.

151
00:07:22,509 --> 00:07:23,875
What did you do to them?

152
00:07:23,877 --> 00:07:26,211
Rachael,
you know Portia's
not good with kids.

153
00:07:26,213 --> 00:07:27,913
It's not her fault.

154
00:07:27,915 --> 00:07:30,882
Kids just don't
take to some people.

155
00:07:30,884 --> 00:07:32,851
I don't know
what you were thinking.

156
00:07:34,220 --> 00:07:35,787
Sorry, he's right.

157
00:07:35,789 --> 00:07:37,756
They're like pit bulls.
They can smell fear.

158
00:07:38,191 --> 00:07:39,591
Good night.

159
00:07:39,593 --> 00:07:40,759
Take them all.

160
00:07:43,162 --> 00:07:46,631
"A man may do no
synne with his wyf,

161
00:07:46,633 --> 00:07:49,668
"Ne hurte hymselven
with his owene knyf."

162
00:07:49,670 --> 00:07:50,936
You know,
if I get Clarence's job,

163
00:07:50,938 --> 00:07:52,704
this would
be my last travel season.

164
00:07:52,706 --> 00:07:54,072
Lovely and wonderful.

165
00:07:54,074 --> 00:07:59,177
And I've ordered everything,
you just have
to pick up the chicken.

166
00:07:59,179 --> 00:08:02,948
And I will stop and get
the famous bean
salad on my way home.

167
00:08:02,950 --> 00:08:05,951
(GRUFF VOICE)
Ah, the famous bean salad.

168
00:08:05,953 --> 00:08:07,719
Is that horrible
Woolf woman
going to be there?

169
00:08:07,721 --> 00:08:08,954
(NORMAL VOICE) Uh.

170
00:08:08,956 --> 00:08:12,991
Helen is the preeminent
Virginia Woolf scholar.

171
00:08:12,993 --> 00:08:15,727
It was quite a coup
to get her from Cambridge.

172
00:08:15,729 --> 00:08:17,529
But I think
she has other plans.

173
00:08:17,531 --> 00:08:19,030
Lovely and wonderful.

174
00:08:24,637 --> 00:08:26,004
Oh, I like this life.

175
00:08:27,073 --> 00:08:28,139
I do, I do.

176
00:08:28,141 --> 00:08:29,207
Good. So do I.

177
00:08:32,545 --> 00:08:37,082
It's so wonderfully simple.

178
00:08:37,084 --> 00:08:39,751
Well, we're simple folk.

179
00:08:40,920 --> 00:08:41,820
(CHUCKLES SOFTLY)

180
00:08:44,223 --> 00:08:45,190
Woof.

181
00:08:45,192 --> 00:08:46,758
Excuse me?

182
00:08:46,760 --> 00:08:49,261
You just patted me
on the head like a dog.

183
00:08:49,263 --> 00:08:50,962
Oh, did I?
(BOTH LAUGH)

184
00:08:51,898 --> 00:08:53,164
Good, doggie.

185
00:08:58,571 --> 00:09:01,006
"Whan that Aprille
with his shoures soote

186
00:09:01,008 --> 00:09:04,609
"The droghte of Marche
hath perced to the roote."

187
00:09:13,219 --> 00:09:15,987
Hi.
Thank you so much
for coming.

188
00:09:15,989 --> 00:09:18,156
My pleasure.
We love
Deerfield students.

189
00:09:18,158 --> 00:09:19,858
Oh, I'm so pleased.
Good.

190
00:09:19,860 --> 00:09:20,792
So, can I help you
bring in your things?

191
00:09:20,794 --> 00:09:22,027
Yes, please.

192
00:09:22,029 --> 00:09:24,129
(VOCALIZING)

193
00:09:24,730 --> 00:09:26,798
(VOCALIZING)

194
00:09:30,937 --> 00:09:32,971
WOMAN: (IN VIDEO)
<i>Princeton,</i>
<i>in the nation's service</i>

195
00:09:32,973 --> 00:09:35,707
<i>and in the service</i>
<i>of all nations.</i>

196
00:09:38,210 --> 00:09:42,280
So, you all want to
know the secret formula
for getting in, right?

197
00:09:43,683 --> 00:09:46,718
Take out your pens.
Write this down.

198
00:09:46,720 --> 00:09:48,687
There is no secret formula.

199
00:09:50,289 --> 00:09:52,290
GPS:  <i>Left on Pony Run Drive.</i>

200
00:09:52,292 --> 00:09:54,626
PORTIA: But I will tell
you what not to do.

201
00:09:54,628 --> 00:09:57,062
No champagne.
No baked goods.

202
00:09:57,064 --> 00:09:59,798
And when you phone,
it is noted in your file.

203
00:09:59,800 --> 00:10:03,268
So put the reins
on those eager
parents of yours.

204
00:10:03,270 --> 00:10:06,271
We're looking for passion.
Whatever it's for,
doesn't matter.

205
00:10:06,739 --> 00:10:07,839
Passion.

206
00:10:07,841 --> 00:10:09,941
GPS:  <i>Right on Shady Lane.</i>

207
00:10:09,943 --> 00:10:12,944
Does that mean
that every Princeton
undergraduate is a genius?

208
00:10:12,946 --> 00:10:15,947
Or a prodigy?
Absolutely not.

209
00:10:15,949 --> 00:10:18,283
Although, we certainly
wouldn't hold it against you.

210
00:10:18,285 --> 00:10:19,884
Almost enough for everyone.

211
00:10:25,691 --> 00:10:29,260
GPS:  <i>Recalculating.</i>
<i>Recalculating.</i>
<i>Recalculating.</i>

212
00:10:34,867 --> 00:10:37,035
<i>Make a U-turn</i>
<i>as soon as possible.</i>

213
00:10:52,251 --> 00:10:53,685
(GRUNTS)

214
00:10:56,922 --> 00:10:58,356
Hey.
Hi.

215
00:11:00,226 --> 00:11:02,127
Portia Nathan.
Princeton admissions office.

216
00:11:02,129 --> 00:11:03,995
I know. I'm John.

217
00:11:03,997 --> 00:11:06,364
Yes. And you said
you went to Dartmouth?
Uh-huh.

218
00:11:06,366 --> 00:11:09,434
Yeah, and my dad,
and his dad,
and his dad.

219
00:11:09,436 --> 00:11:11,102
Um, a legacy.

220
00:11:11,104 --> 00:11:12,671
A legacy of what,
I'm not really sure.

221
00:11:14,273 --> 00:11:16,441
So, you're
chopping some wood here?

222
00:11:16,443 --> 00:11:19,778
I'm showing them
how to build a sustainable
irrigation system.

223
00:11:19,780 --> 00:11:21,379
This is
my Third World
Development class.

224
00:11:21,381 --> 00:11:23,114
Well, nice ax.

225
00:11:23,949 --> 00:11:25,150
Great ax.

226
00:11:26,819 --> 00:11:28,119
So, let's get to it.
Yeah.

227
00:11:29,455 --> 00:11:31,022
(VOCALIZING)

228
00:11:34,326 --> 00:11:36,094
(VOCALIZING)

229
00:11:45,705 --> 00:11:48,273
Hi, there.
You all want to know

230
00:11:48,275 --> 00:11:50,775
the secret formula
for getting in, right?

231
00:11:54,146 --> 00:11:55,714
Well, take out
your pens.

232
00:12:00,753 --> 00:12:02,053
Take 'em out.

233
00:12:04,924 --> 00:12:06,858
Yes?

234
00:12:06,860 --> 00:12:09,127
I'll tell you
what I'd like to know.

235
00:12:09,129 --> 00:12:11,796
Why should I apply
to an elitist institution

236
00:12:11,798 --> 00:12:15,200
with a history
of anti-black, anti-gay,
and anti-female oppression?

237
00:12:15,202 --> 00:12:17,936
Well, actually,
I reject that stereotype...

238
00:12:17,938 --> 00:12:21,506
Speaking of rejection,
don't you reject
99.9% of your applicants?

