as a professional courtesy,

957
00:46:34,259 --> 00:46:37,293
I can send you books,
resources,

958
00:46:37,295 --> 00:46:39,228
everything that
one might need. Okay?

959
00:46:39,230 --> 00:46:40,329
Great.
Goodbye.

960
00:46:42,466 --> 00:46:43,900
What the hell was that?

961
00:46:43,902 --> 00:46:45,868
I put my heart into it.
<i>Fútbol.</i>

962
00:46:47,070 --> 00:46:49,071
I'll give you 10 bucks
if you can do it again.

963
00:46:53,243 --> 00:46:54,343
They grow up so
damn fast, don't they?

964
00:46:54,345 --> 00:46:55,845
Yeah.

965
00:46:55,847 --> 00:46:57,113
Which one is yours?

966
00:46:57,447 --> 00:46:58,881
Yeah.

967
00:47:05,088 --> 00:47:06,589
With a megaphone.

968
00:47:06,591 --> 00:47:09,125
Yeah. (SIGHS)
Right? Exactly.

969
00:47:20,337 --> 00:47:22,371
Okay, okay, I heard you.
I heard you.

970
00:47:22,373 --> 00:47:24,574
Let me.
It takes a village.

971
00:47:24,576 --> 00:47:26,943
Get your hands
off my baby!

972
00:47:26,945 --> 00:47:28,845
No, I was just helping.
What are you doing?

973
00:47:28,847 --> 00:47:29,879
Everybody
needs a little help.

974
00:47:29,881 --> 00:47:31,180
Get out.

975
00:47:31,582 --> 00:47:33,049
I'm helping you.

976
00:47:33,051 --> 00:47:34,183
WOMAN: Come on. Come on.

977
00:47:34,618 --> 00:47:35,918
Right now.

978
00:47:35,920 --> 00:47:37,887
I'm not...
I'm not a creep.

979
00:47:53,470 --> 00:47:55,438
JEREMIAH:
When I was eight years old,
I realized my teachers

980
00:47:55,440 --> 00:47:57,406
were not going
to be able to teach me.

981
00:47:57,408 --> 00:48:00,276
So I became an autodidact.

982
00:48:00,278 --> 00:48:01,377
I read everything.

983
00:48:05,450 --> 00:48:10,019
<i>mainly because</i>
<i>I didn't know how other</i>
<i>people lived their lives.</i>

984
00:48:17,895 --> 00:48:20,196
<i>I learned several years ago</i>
<i>that I was adopted,</i>

985
00:48:20,198 --> 00:48:24,567
<i>that my parents</i>
<i>tried so hard</i>
<i>to have on their own.</i>

986
00:48:24,569 --> 00:48:27,103
<i>I think my voracious reading</i>
<i>came from a deep longing</i>

987
00:48:27,105 --> 00:48:28,104
<i>for something</i>
<i>that was missing.</i>

988
00:48:29,339 --> 00:48:30,640
<i>I was searching</i>
<i>for someone.</i>

989
00:48:30,642 --> 00:48:32,074
<i>For my story.</i>

990
00:48:32,076 --> 00:48:33,643
(SIGHS)

991
00:48:33,645 --> 00:48:35,044
<i>To not feel so alone.</i>

992
00:48:41,018 --> 00:48:43,019
MARK: Portia?

993
00:48:44,554 --> 00:48:46,022
(GROANS)

994
00:48:46,024 --> 00:48:47,490
I knew you were taking
this all rather hard,

995
00:48:47,492 --> 00:48:49,625
but I thought by now
you'd be back on your feet.

996
00:48:49,627 --> 00:48:50,559
What?

997
00:48:51,194 --> 00:48:53,362
It kills me.

998
00:48:53,364 --> 00:48:54,964
It really kills me.
You'll get through this.

999
00:48:54,966 --> 00:48:56,265
You think...

1000
00:48:56,267 --> 00:48:57,433
I know it seems impossible,
but you will.

1001
00:48:57,435 --> 00:48:59,068
No, this has
nothing to do with you.

1002
00:48:59,070 --> 00:49:00,369
(SHUSHING)

1003
00:49:00,371 --> 00:49:01,637
It's okay.
It's okay. I understand.

1004
00:49:01,639 --> 00:49:03,005
No, really.

1005
00:49:03,007 --> 00:49:04,607
(CYCLE BELL RINGING)

1006
00:49:04,609 --> 00:49:07,643
Oh, Christ!
I have to go.
Hang on in there!

1007
00:49:09,647 --> 00:49:13,382
Il Forno is one
of my favorite
restaurants, too.

1008
00:49:13,384 --> 00:49:15,084
That's amazing.
I know.

1009
00:49:15,086 --> 00:49:16,352
Hey.

1010
00:49:16,354 --> 00:49:18,154
Portia, sweetie,
you feeling all right?

1011
00:49:19,690 --> 00:49:21,724
Just terrific. Thanks.
Oh, good.

1012
00:49:21,726 --> 00:49:23,626
Then I think there
was an evaluation card

1013
00:49:23,628 --> 00:49:25,695
that was placed
on the wrong file.

1014
00:49:25,697 --> 00:49:28,164
A Jeremiah Balakian.

1015
00:49:28,166 --> 00:49:29,365
Balakian.

1016
00:49:29,700 --> 00:49:31,000
Balakian.

1017
00:49:32,302 --> 00:49:34,303
Balakian.
Balakian.

1018
00:49:34,305 --> 00:49:35,738
I think.

1019
00:49:35,740 --> 00:49:38,741
You didn't mean
to put "High Consider,"
did you?

1020
00:49:38,743 --> 00:49:40,710
Um, let me see.

1021
00:49:44,681 --> 00:49:46,215
No, that's right.

1022
00:49:46,217 --> 00:49:48,184
But he has
D's and F's
and suspensions.

1023
00:49:48,186 --> 00:49:52,221
But did you
notice that he also got
fives on all eight AP exams

1024
00:49:52,223 --> 00:49:55,191
without ever
taking any AP courses?

1025
00:49:55,193 --> 00:49:58,127
Yes. I'm going
to investigate that.
That's impossible.

1026
00:49:58,129 --> 00:50:02,765
No, apparently not,
if the child in question
is a unique, special child.

1027
00:50:04,334 --> 00:50:06,502
This isn't a child.
It's an applicant.

1028
00:50:06,504 --> 00:50:08,637
He's got no
extracurriculars at all.

1029
00:50:08,639 --> 00:50:10,373
The counselor
at his old high school
said he was shocked

1030
00:50:10,375 --> 00:50:12,041
Jeremiah was even
applying to college.

1031
00:50:12,043 --> 00:50:13,676
He's an autodidact.

1032
00:50:13,678 --> 00:50:16,545
He's an advanced reader
from the age of eight.

1033
00:50:16,547 --> 00:50:21,684
Leonardo da Vinci
was an autodidact.
So was Benjamin Franklin.

1034
00:50:21,686 --> 00:50:24,453
Oh, did this Balakian kid
discover electricity
or paint the  <i>Mona Lisa?</i>

1035
00:50:24,455 --> 00:50:26,322
I must have missed
that in his file.

1036
00:50:26,324 --> 00:50:27,790
He's a great kid.

1037
00:50:27,792 --> 00:50:29,525
CLARENCE: Portia, dear,

1038
00:50:29,527 --> 00:50:31,660
take a deep breath.

1039
00:50:31,662 --> 00:50:32,695
Teamwork, remember?

1040
00:50:32,697 --> 00:50:34,163
Of course.

1041
00:50:34,165 --> 00:50:36,365
I'm sorry.
No, I'm sorry.

1042
00:50:36,367 --> 00:50:38,734
I forgot
you're in a
very fragile state.

1043
00:50:38,736 --> 00:50:41,404
Maybe you'd like
to step outside
and see how fragile I am.

1044
00:50:45,075 --> 00:50:47,510
Only kidding!
Only kidding.

1045
00:50:47,512 --> 00:50:50,780
Just a little levity
to enhance the teamwork.

1046
00:50:52,215 --> 00:50:54,717
Thank you for
your thoughts, Corinne.

1047
00:50:56,653 --> 00:50:58,120
(LAUGHS)

1048
00:50:58,122 --> 00:50:59,755
He's never getting in.
Never.

1049
00:50:59,757 --> 00:51:01,657
Calm down.
There's something
great I want to show you.

1050
00:51:01,659 --> 00:51:03,626
It turns out Jeremiah was
a state champion in...

1051
00:51:03,628 --> 00:51:06,729
You know what?
It's better if you
see it for yourself.

1052
00:51:06,731 --> 00:51:08,697
He's gonna be doing it
at Nelson's birthday party.

1053
00:51:08,699 --> 00:51:12,301
<i>intellectual passion.</i>
<i>Everything</i>
<i>the books talk about.</i>

1054
00:51:12,303 --> 00:51:13,636
Oh, State champion!
Thank God.

1055
00:51:13,638 --> 00:51:18,240
<i>So, I'll send you</i>
<i>the address</i>
<i>to Nelson's birthday party.</i>

1056
00:51:18,242 --> 00:51:19,608
It's at my parents' house.

1057
00:51:19,610 --> 00:51:21,243
I'll be there.
Good.

1058
00:51:23,413 --> 00:51:25,147
Is she coming to my party?
Mmm-hmm.

1059
00:51:27,851 --> 00:51:29,218
Why do you like
her so much?

1060
00:51:29,220 --> 00:51:31,487
I don't know.
She's weird.

1061
00:51:31,489 --> 00:51:32,688
She is indeed.

1062
00:51:32,690 --> 00:51:34,256
Doesn't matter anyway.
Right?

1063
00:51:34,258 --> 00:51:35,391
Sure it matters.

1064
00:51:39,162 --> 00:51:42,431
But about this
Spanish test.

1065
00:51:42,433 --> 00:51:44,467
This is your third
"try harder" in a row.

1066
00:51:44,469 --> 00:51:47,536
<i>Señor</i>Garcia says you have
an aptitude for languages.

1067
00:51:47,538 --> 00:51:48,571
What if I don't?

1068
00:51:49,840 --> 00:51:52,441
What if I don't have
an aptitude for languages?

1069
00:51:52,443 --> 00:51:54,610
What if I'm not
a genius like Jeremiah?

1070
00:51:54,612 --> 00:51:57,346
I don't want you
to be a genius,
I'm not a genius,

1071
00:51:57,348 --> 00:51:58,881
but I want you to be able
to get by in the world.

1072
00:51:58,883 --> 00:52:00,616
Whatever.
<i>En español.</i>

1073
00:52:00,618 --> 00:52:02,585
Whatever! I have class.

1074
00:52:05,155 --> 00:52:08,157
Even Beckett emerged
from Gogol's  <i>Overcoat.</i>

1075
00:52:08,159 --> 00:52:09,692
Not to mention Pinter...

1076
00:52:09,694 --> 00:52:11,360
PORTIA: Professor Polokov.
Yes.

1077
00:52:11,362 --> 00:52:13,562
Portia Nathan.
Yes, the sad lady.

1078
00:52:13,564 --> 00:52:15,364
The sad lady?
That's not really
how I think of myself.

1079
00:52:15,366 --> 00:52:16,699
How is your mother?

1080
00:52:16,701 --> 00:52:18,400
She's fine.

1081
00:52:18,402 --> 00:52:20,703
So, I wonder,
would you consider

1082
00:52:20,705 --> 00:52:23,706
conducting some supplementary
admissions interviews?

1083
00:52:23,708 --> 00:52:25,708
A scholar
of your stature
would carry

1084
00:52:25,710 --> 00:52:27,676
a huge amount of weight
with the committee.

1085
00:52:27,678 --> 00:52:30,880
In fact, there is one
extremely unusual applicant

1086
00:52:30,882 --> 00:52:33,582
who's shown a strong interest
in literature and philosophy.

1087
00:52:33,584 --> 00:52:36,852
Why would I want to speak
with a high school student?

1088
00:52:36,854 --> 00:52:40,856
Of course, perhaps
we could make some
sort of arrangement.

1089
00:52:40,858 --> 00:52:42,691
SUSANNAH: I can't believe
you're pimping me.

1090
00:52:42,693 --> 00:52:45,895
I'm not pimping you.
He's a fan of your writing.

1091
00:52:45,897 --> 00:52:48,430
And I need him
to meet this applicant.

1092
00:52:48,432 --> 00:52:50,499
Besides, when's the last time
you went to a party?

1093
00:52:50,501 --> 00:52:52,701
With racist jockey
statues? Never.

1094
00:52:52,703 --> 00:52:53,769
Yeah, those are
pretty weird.

1095
00:53:00,677 --> 00:53:02,478
Hey, Portia!
Thanks for coming
to my party!

1096
00:53:02,480 --> 00:53:03,746
Hi, Nelson,
happy birthday!

1097
00:53:04,881 --> 00:53:07,216
Hey! I'm glad you
could make it.

1098
00:53:07,218 --> 00:53:09,185
So, this is
your parents' place?

1099
00:53:09,187 --> 00:53:11,820
Hmm. Yeah.
Well, my mom's now.

1100
00:53:11,822 --> 00:53:14,190
My dad passed
away a few months ago.

1101
00:53:14,192 --> 00:53:15,457
Oh, I'm sorry.
No.

1102
00:53:16,927 --> 00:53:18,561
It's nice to
see you again.

1103
00:53:18,563 --> 00:53:20,229
You're not packing heat
by any chance, are you?

1104
00:53:20,231 --> 00:53:21,497
Should I be?

1105
00:53:21,499 --> 00:53:22,631
No, we're all friendlies.

1106
00:53:23,333 --> 00:53:24,667
So, what is this?

1107
00:53:24,669 --> 00:53:27,870
That is a fossil
from the Jurassic era.

1108
00:53:27,872 --> 00:53:30,873
It's been in the same place
for 150 million years.

1109
00:53:30,875 --> 00:53:32,208
Oh, cool!

1110
00:53:32,210 --> 00:53:34,443
Welcome, welcome, welcome.

1111
00:53:34,445 --> 00:53:35,678
Mom, I would like
you to meet...

1112
00:53:35,680 --> 00:53:37,880
I'm Johnny's mother,
Mrs. Pressman.

1113
00:53:37,882 --> 00:53:43,519
Ah, no. No, we are friends.
Just friendly acquaintances.
Portia Nathan.

1114
00:53:43,521 --> 00:53:45,754
Of course.
What am I thinking?

1115
00:53:45,756 --> 00:53:51,427
He can't love anything
that's less than
a 10-hour flight from JFK.

1116
00:53:51,429 --> 00:53:52,761
Maybe we don't have to go.
Right, Grandma?

1117
00:53:52,763 --> 00:53:54,230
Nelson.

1118
00:53:54,232 --> 00:53:56,265
You're absolutely
right, Nelson.

1119
00:53:56,267 --> 00:54:00,402
There's nothing wrong
with staying in the same
place for a while.

1120
00:54:00,404 --> 00:54:03,439
Ask Portia. She's
been in the same
job for 16 years!

1121
00:54:03,441 --> 00:54:04,940
Yeah. And it's
a travesty, Nelson.

1122
00:54:04,942 --> 00:54:07,676
Portia was president
of her high school class.

1123
00:54:07,678 --> 00:54:09,612
Mom.
And she resigned
in protest over

1124
00:54:09,614 --> 00:54:11,547
funding
for the girls'
sports program.

1125
00:54:11,549 --> 00:54:14,383
She led
a school-wide walkout.

1126
00:54:14,385 --> 00:54:15,684
And the relevance
of all this is?

1127
00:54:15,686 --> 00:54:20,256
When you were nine months old,
you could walk.

1128
00:54:20,258 --> 00:54:21,991
She actually walked.

1129
00:54:21,993 --> 00:54:25,527
I don't mean
just stumble walking
like an infant or a toddler.

1130
00:54:25,529 --> 00:54:27,763
She walked with
absolute certainty.

1131
00:54:27,765 --> 00:54:30,399
One day I saw her tumble
over her shoelaces, John,

1132
00:54:30,401 --> 00:54:32,768
she did not cry,
she didn't fall down,

1133
00:54:32,770 --> 00:54:36,939
she sat down, carefully,
tied her shoelaces
in a double knot...

1134
00:54:36,941 --> 00:54:38,941
(LAUGHING)
...got up and kept going.

1135
00:54:38,943 --> 00:54:40,576
At nine months old.

1136
00:54:40,578 --> 00:54:42,378
There are a lot
of holes in that story.

1137
00:54:42,380 --> 00:54:45,748
You were fearless.
You were born an Amazon.

1138
00:54:45,750 --> 00:54:47,516
That's amazing.
I love it!

1139
00:54:47,518 --> 00:54:49,652
And what makes you think
she needs your approval?

1140
00:54:49,654 --> 00:54:52,521
Okay, that's
enough crazytown.

1141
00:54:52,523 --> 00:54:53,756
When Johnny got
admitted to Harvard Law...

1142
00:54:53,758 --> 00:54:55,424
Oh, God.

1143
00:54:55,426 --> 00:54:58,694
...he decided to go
and live in Outer
Mongolia instead.

1144
00:54:58,696 --> 00:55:00,763
Outer Mongolia?
You know what, Portia,

1145
00:55:00,765 --> 00:55:02,564
I'm with you,
enough crazytown.

1146
00:55:02,566 --> 00:55:05,901
Have another vat
of gin there, Mom.

1147
00:55:05,903 --> 00:55:08,671
Ms. Nathan,
Vladimir Polokov.

1148
00:55:15,512 --> 00:55:18,047
You are just as
beautiful today
as you were 30 years ago.

1149
00:55:18,049 --> 00:55:20,349
I just had a mastectomy.

1150
00:55:20,351 --> 00:55:22,451
I was just translated
into Finnish.

1151
00:55:22,453 --> 00:55:23,952
(CHUCKLING)

1152
00:55:23,954 --> 00:55:24,987
(SPEAKING FINNISH)

1153
00:55:24,989 --> 00:55:26,322
Brilliant.

1154
00:55:27,324 --> 00:55:28,857
May I get you
some iced tea?

1155
00:55:28,859 --> 00:55:30,893
Or something stronger,
perhaps?

1156
00:55:30,895 --> 00:55:33,429
Why not.
I'll stroll with you.

1157
00:55:33,431 --> 00:55:36,598
I'd love to.
It would be a pleasure.

1158
00:55:36,600 --> 00:55:41,337
It was a pleasure.
Your lawn jockeys
are just outstanding.

1159
00:55:41,339 --> 00:55:42,404
Aren't they fun?

1160
00:55:46,343 --> 00:55:50,546
And now, with a special
performance for Nelson
on his big day...

1161
00:55:50,548 --> 00:55:51,814
(WHOOPING)

1162
00:55:51,816 --> 00:55:53,982
(ALL APPLAUDING)

1163
00:55:53,984 --> 00:55:57,119
...performing
the act that won him
honorable mention

1164
00:55:57,121 --> 00:56:00,456
at the New Hampshire
state championships,
put your hands together,

1165
00:56:00,458 --> 00:56:02,124
(DRUMMING)

1166
00:56:02,126 --> 00:56:04,927
put your hands together,

1167
00:56:04,929 --> 00:56:06,562
for Jeremiah Balakian!

1168
00:56:11,634 --> 00:56:14,536
I want to dedicate
this performance to Nelson.

1169
00:56:14,538 --> 00:56:15,904
Happy birthday, pal.

1170
00:56:17,874 --> 00:56:19,942
Honorable mention?
I thought you said he won.

1171
00:56:19,944 --> 00:56:21,443
He was robbed.

1172
00:56:21,445 --> 00:56:23,979
This is my other friend,
René Descartes.

1173
00:56:24,748 --> 00:56:25,981
Say, hello, René.

1174
00:56:25,983 --> 00:56:26,982
ALL: Hello, René.

1175
00:56:28,418 --> 00:56:29,618
How are you, René?

1176
00:56:30,987 --> 00:56:35,157
I think,
therefore I am.

1177
00:56:35,159 --> 00:56:37,926
(LAUGHING)

1178
00:56:37,928 --> 00:56:40,763
Did you say you're pink,
therefore you're ham?

1179
00:56:40,765 --> 00:56:43,732
Do you have any advice
for a young man, René?

1180
00:56:43,734 --> 00:56:50,139
Whatever you do,
don't put the horse
before Descartes.

1181
00:56:50,141 --> 00:56:51,974
(LAUGHING)

1182
00:56:54,511 --> 00:56:58,414
Hey, do you guys
want to see Descartes
philosophize backwards?

1183
00:56:59,082 --> 00:57:01,984
I think, therefore I am.

1184
00:57:01,986 --> 00:57:03,018
Oh, God.

1185
00:57:03,887 --> 00:57:05,053
That's terrible.

1186
00:57:10,860 --> 00:57:12,561
What was that?

1187
00:57:12,563 --> 00:57:14,129
Come on, that showed
originality, depth.

1188
00:57:14,131 --> 00:57:15,664
Are you kidding me?

1189
00:57:15,666 --> 00:57:16,698
Here, from the
Island of Misfit Toys,

1190
00:57:16,700 --> 00:57:18,000
we bring you
Jeremiah Balakian!

1191
00:57:18,002 --> 00:57:19,134
Are those birds?

1192
00:57:19,136 --> 00:57:20,669
Those are doves.

1193
00:57:20,671 --> 00:57:21,804
