01:11:30,954 --> 01:11:34,689
upon first reading,
as we all sometimes do.

1435
01:11:34,691 --> 01:11:37,759
I think this girl's
self-knowledge
is impressive.

1436
01:11:37,761 --> 01:11:39,560
She's an excellent candidate.

1437
01:11:41,797 --> 01:11:42,764
CLARENCE: Vote.

1438
01:11:45,934 --> 01:11:46,801
Oh.
(LAUGHING)

1439
01:11:47,569 --> 01:11:48,670
Very good.

1440
01:11:55,044 --> 01:12:00,315
Dashiel Weld Broward,
fourth-generation legacy.

1441
01:12:01,650 --> 01:12:03,685
4.0.

1442
01:12:03,687 --> 01:12:05,653
Captain of his sailing club.

1443
01:12:05,655 --> 01:12:08,489
He led them to victory
three years in a row.

1444
01:12:08,491 --> 01:12:09,724
CORINNE: SATs?

1445
01:12:09,726 --> 01:12:12,727
Uh, 660, 710, 600.

1446
01:12:12,729 --> 01:12:13,828
He's just one of those kids
that doesn't test well.

1447
01:12:14,830 --> 01:12:18,333
But, oh,
can he read the wind.

1448
01:12:18,335 --> 01:12:20,435
So what you're
saying is that an unusual

1449
01:12:20,437 --> 01:12:22,737
candidate's strengths
in some areas

1450
01:12:22,739 --> 01:12:27,709
really do outweigh major,
and I mean major,
weakness elsewhere.

1451
01:12:30,412 --> 01:12:31,713
Yes.

1452
01:12:32,414 --> 01:12:34,982
Let's vote then.
For acceptance?

1453
01:12:40,656 --> 01:12:42,990
Aput Kunayak
from Nome, Alaska.

1454
01:12:43,992 --> 01:12:46,361
Managed to take
five AP classes

1455
01:12:46,363 --> 01:12:48,796
while working
on his father's reindeer farm

1456
01:12:48,798 --> 01:12:53,868
and starting and
running a shelter
for homeless sled dogs.

1457
01:12:53,870 --> 01:12:56,504
Had suffered from ADD,
but overcame it

1458
01:12:56,506 --> 01:12:58,806
to become a leader
in his high school.

1459
01:12:58,808 --> 01:13:01,542
He'd be
the first in his family
to attend college.

1460
01:13:01,544 --> 01:13:04,545
Now, Ben,
as you know,
we have room

1461
01:13:04,547 --> 01:13:07,715
for very few
of these iffy students.

1462
01:13:07,717 --> 01:13:10,084
But then again,
we have to make room
for the exceptional, right?

1463
01:13:11,587 --> 01:13:12,653
Let's vote.

1464
01:13:25,701 --> 01:13:28,069
Aput Kunayak.

1465
01:13:31,507 --> 01:13:33,808
Are you gonna
give me the file?

1466
01:13:33,810 --> 01:13:38,579
At last,
we come to the end,
the Northeast.

1467
01:13:38,581 --> 01:13:41,616
Portia, please begin.

1468
01:13:42,651 --> 01:13:43,718
(SIGHS) Thank you.

1469
01:13:46,488 --> 01:13:49,724
Richard Guinness,
Rye Country Day School,

1470
01:13:49,726 --> 01:13:53,528
state champion
in the 138-pound
wrestling class,

1471
01:13:53,530 --> 01:13:56,864
played Rolfe in
the school production
of  <i>The Sound of Music.</i>

1472
01:13:58,066 --> 01:14:01,602
Chess club,
makes an excellent soufflé.

1473
01:14:01,604 --> 01:14:02,904
Member of the team,
but not a leader.

1474
01:14:04,506 --> 01:14:07,675
Backbone
of the woodwinds section

1475
01:14:07,677 --> 01:14:10,044
was the highest praise he got.

1476
01:14:10,046 --> 01:14:12,046
He is the kind of student

1477
01:14:12,048 --> 01:14:14,048
you could always
call upon to help with

1478
01:14:14,050 --> 01:14:15,817
Martin Luther
King Day activities.

1479
01:14:16,952 --> 01:14:18,686
Who isn't?

1480
01:14:18,688 --> 01:14:22,657
That's 28 denies in a row.

1481
01:14:23,559 --> 01:14:26,494
Come on, Portia,
make us fall in love.

1482
01:14:26,496 --> 01:14:27,695
Okay, let's see.

1483
01:14:30,632 --> 01:14:31,699
Ah.

1484
01:14:34,069 --> 01:14:35,736
Jeremiah Balakian.

1485
01:14:40,576 --> 01:14:42,944
Jeremiah is our first
applicant from Quest,

1486
01:14:42,946 --> 01:14:45,646
a new school
in New Hampshire.

1487
01:14:45,648 --> 01:14:47,715
Developmental,
but academically rigorous.

1488
01:14:48,250 --> 01:14:50,251
Jeremiah is an only child.

1489
01:14:50,253 --> 01:14:52,653
Parents both
work at a Stop-N-Go.

1490
01:14:52,655 --> 01:14:54,789
Neither of them
attended college.

1491
01:14:54,791 --> 01:14:59,994
The first three years
of his high school life
were a disaster.

1492
01:14:59,996 --> 01:15:02,263
If you're wondering
why you are even
listening to this,

1493
01:15:02,265 --> 01:15:07,902
Jeremiah is also
a self-described autodidact
since the age of eight.

1494
01:15:07,904 --> 01:15:11,906
In fact, he is
the most well-read person
I have met.

1495
01:15:11,908 --> 01:15:12,974
Ever.

1496
01:15:12,976 --> 01:15:18,813
And why?
For his resume?
To impress someone?

1497
01:15:18,815 --> 01:15:22,817
For the sake of learning,
his passion for knowledge.

1498
01:15:24,653 --> 01:15:26,120
He had no plans
to attend college

1499
01:15:26,122 --> 01:15:29,290
until this past fall
when he switched to Quest

1500
01:15:29,292 --> 01:15:34,962
and came into contact
with teachers
who recognized his potential.

1501
01:15:34,964 --> 01:15:39,534
Last spring,
he took the SATs
and eight AP tests.

1502
01:15:39,536 --> 01:15:41,869
Wait, so he took
AP classes?

1503
01:15:41,871 --> 01:15:45,606
No AP classes,
no SAT prep courses.

1504
01:15:45,608 --> 01:15:48,743
But he got 5's
on all eight APs,

1505
01:15:48,745 --> 01:15:53,814
and 790,
780 and 790 on the SATs.

1506
01:15:54,182 --> 01:15:55,716
That's amazing.

1507
01:15:55,718 --> 01:15:56,651
I'm sorry,
what did you say?

1508
01:15:56,653 --> 01:15:58,019
That's amazing.

1509
01:15:58,021 --> 01:15:59,921
Amazing!
It's amazing.
Exactly.

1510
01:16:01,323 --> 01:16:04,792
Do you think he can handle
an intense academic community?

1511
01:16:04,794 --> 01:16:05,893
Thank you.
That's a great question.

1512
01:16:05,895 --> 01:16:10,031
The director
of his new school
says he is

1513
01:16:10,033 --> 01:16:12,700
"idiosyncratic, cerebral,

1514
01:16:12,702 --> 01:16:15,069
"a true original
whose abilities would lift

1515
01:16:15,071 --> 01:16:18,239
"the level of discourse
in any class he enrolled in."

1516
01:16:18,241 --> 01:16:19,707
You seem
passionate about him.

1517
01:16:19,709 --> 01:16:21,609
I am.

1518
01:16:21,611 --> 01:16:25,680
So what was his GPA,
I mean, before Quest?

1519
01:16:26,214 --> 01:16:28,950
D+, 1.5.

1520
01:16:28,952 --> 01:16:33,120
He was a lost kid,
and then he was found.

1521
01:16:35,190 --> 01:16:38,259
So, Corinne,
you were second reader,
I see you wrote "Deny."

1522
01:16:38,961 --> 01:16:40,161
Any second thoughts?

1523
01:16:44,633 --> 01:16:46,701
Well, he is like no
other applicant we
have ever considered.

1524
01:16:48,604 --> 01:16:50,204
His alumni interview
was not so great.

1525
01:16:50,206 --> 01:16:51,606
That guy sounded
like a jerk.

1526
01:16:54,276 --> 01:16:55,876
(LAUGHING)

1527
01:16:55,878 --> 01:16:58,913
And he has
a positive
recommendation from

1528
01:16:58,915 --> 01:17:01,248
no less of a scholar
than Vladimir Polokov.

1529
01:17:05,787 --> 01:17:10,024
Okay, maybe from
our perspective, he
could have done more,

1530
01:17:10,026 --> 01:17:14,629
made himself
more of a resume
and a paper trail,

1531
01:17:14,631 --> 01:17:18,265
but he took
himself from nowhere
to where he is today.

1532
01:17:19,267 --> 01:17:20,968
He educated himself,

1533
01:17:20,970 --> 01:17:24,005
purely by instinct,

1534
01:17:24,007 --> 01:17:26,007
not because he wants
to put away
his mother's killer.

1535
01:17:28,076 --> 01:17:31,145
He was as isolated
as someone in Nome, Alaska.

1536
01:17:31,147 --> 01:17:32,780
He was alone.

1537
01:17:32,782 --> 01:17:34,081
He was completely alone.

1538
01:17:36,418 --> 01:17:37,952
You know, and maybe
if his parents had been rich,

1539
01:17:37,954 --> 01:17:39,854
he would have
been exposed to more.

1540
01:17:41,857 --> 01:17:44,392
We have to make
room for these kids.

1541
01:17:50,032 --> 01:17:51,799
(SNIFFLING)

1542
01:17:51,801 --> 01:17:54,235
We have to make room
for kids like these.

1543
01:17:58,240 --> 01:18:00,408
Clarence, you told us
at the beginning of the year

1544
01:18:00,410 --> 01:18:02,777
to find that
undiscovered gem.

1545
01:18:05,080 --> 01:18:06,847
I found him.

1546
01:18:13,989 --> 01:18:15,690
CLARENCE:
Well, let's vote.

1547
01:18:15,692 --> 01:18:17,958
All in favor of admission?

1548
01:18:36,244 --> 01:18:37,978
He also received
an honorable mention

1549
01:18:37,980 --> 01:18:40,414
at the state
finals of ventriloquism.

1550
01:18:40,416 --> 01:18:41,782
We are in
the middle of a vote.

1551
01:18:45,787 --> 01:18:46,921
Brandt?

1552
01:18:49,991 --> 01:18:52,226
I'm sorry, Portia.
I just think

1553
01:18:52,228 --> 01:18:54,261
he's got a little
too much to overcome.

1554
01:18:55,263 --> 01:18:58,065
I mean,
the kid was
in Special Ed.

1555
01:18:58,067 --> 01:19:02,369
subconsciously identify
with applicants who
remind us of ourselves,

1556
01:19:02,371 --> 01:19:03,971
but, honey, no.

1557
01:19:07,309 --> 01:19:10,010
Okay, then. Deny.

1558
01:19:10,012 --> 01:19:13,280
Wait! Polokov
called him inspirational!

1559
01:19:13,282 --> 01:19:15,783
Portia,
please, sit down.

1560
01:19:23,125 --> 01:19:24,992
It's too risky.

1561
01:19:26,895 --> 01:19:29,997
He's just not
Princeton material.

1562
01:19:31,867 --> 01:19:35,002
I'm actually surprised
that you thought he was.

1563
01:19:43,411 --> 01:19:44,912
(CLEARS THROAT)

1564
01:19:46,782 --> 01:19:52,219
Tanisha Jones,
Brearley School, Manhattan.

1565
01:19:52,221 --> 01:19:57,291
GPA 4.3,
speaks semi-fluent Mandarin.

1566
01:19:57,293 --> 01:19:58,893
A CAPPELLA SINGERS:
<i>Two, three, four.</i>

1567
01:19:58,895 --> 01:20:00,528
(SCATTING)

1568
01:20:05,333 --> 01:20:06,967
(SINGING A CAPPELLA)

1569
01:20:57,552 --> 01:20:59,153
(TELEPHONE RINGING)

1570
01:21:05,861 --> 01:21:07,428
Portia Nathan.

1571
01:21:07,430 --> 01:21:10,497
BOB:  <i>Hey. This is Bob</i>
<i>Barrow from Hotchkiss.</i>

1572
01:21:10,499 --> 01:21:13,934
<i>I wanted to talk to you</i>
<i>about one of our applicants.</i>

1573
01:21:13,936 --> 01:21:16,203
All decisions
have been made.

1574
01:21:16,205 --> 01:21:18,239
<i>Yes, but I wanted you</i>
<i>to know that</i>

1575
01:21:18,241 --> 01:21:19,974
<i>Jesse Bolton</i>
<i>is going to Yale.</i>

1576
01:21:19,976 --> 01:21:25,045
<i>Even though</i>
<i>he's a legacy, he is</i>
<i>definitely going to Yale.</i>

1577
01:21:25,047 --> 01:21:28,249
<i>Huh.</i>
<i>So, look, if you accepted him,</i>
<i>maybe that</i>

1578
01:21:28,251 --> 01:21:30,618
<i>place can go</i>
<i>to another</i>
<i>of our students.</i>

1579
01:21:30,620 --> 01:21:34,054
<i>Instead of Jesse</i>
<i>just rejecting Princeton.</i>

1580
01:21:34,056 --> 01:21:37,424
Thank you for your call,
but all decisions
are absolutely final.

1581
01:21:37,426 --> 01:21:38,926
No changes can be made.

1582
01:21:38,928 --> 01:21:41,295
<i>Uh, yes, but I...</i>

1583
01:22:15,964 --> 01:22:17,131
(READING CARD ALOUD)

1584
01:23:24,232 --> 01:23:26,200
I'm sorry
you feel that way.

1585
01:23:26,202 --> 01:23:28,635
No, there isn't
an appeals process.

1586
01:23:28,637 --> 01:23:30,704
How wonderful
Elissa got so
many acceptances.

1587
01:23:30,706 --> 01:23:34,141
Harvard and Yale, too?

1588
01:23:34,143 --> 01:23:35,642
Listen, I'd love
to talk to you about

1589
01:23:35,644 --> 01:23:37,644
the financial aid
package we could offer.

1590
01:23:37,646 --> 01:23:40,647
No, seriously.
I'm so happy, too.

1591
01:23:40,649 --> 01:23:44,251
No, you rock. No.

1592
01:23:44,253 --> 01:23:47,087
Yes, I know he is a legacy.
And I certainly understand

1593
01:23:47,089 --> 01:23:48,522
why you would
never want to give

1594
01:23:48,524 --> 01:23:50,424
another penny to this
university ever again.

1595
01:23:52,027 --> 01:23:53,727
Wow. That is a new one.

1596
01:24:05,340 --> 01:24:07,074
(CELL PHONE BUZZING)

1597
01:24:12,481 --> 01:24:17,084
Hey, I have somebody here
who wants to talk to you.
(CHUCKLES)

1598
01:24:17,086 --> 01:24:18,218
I got in.

1599
01:24:18,220 --> 01:24:19,586
Yes, I know.

1600
01:24:19,588 --> 01:24:22,689
This is the best
day of my life.

1601
01:24:22,691 --> 01:24:25,692
Best day of your life, huh?
Well, that's good.

1602
01:24:25,694 --> 01:24:28,162
Good. That's...
I'm very happy.

1603
01:24:28,164 --> 01:24:29,396
(JEREMIAH YELLS)

1604
01:24:29,398 --> 01:24:33,067
<i>Look, we're having</i>
<i>a school dance here tonight.</i>

1605
01:24:33,069 --> 01:24:34,334
I think you should
come and celebrate.

1606
01:24:37,539 --> 01:24:41,208
Oh, there you are.
Clarence wants to see you.

1607
01:24:41,210 --> 01:24:44,078
Yes, thank you.
I've been expecting that.

1608
01:24:44,080 --> 01:24:46,246
I have to go.
I'll call you later.

1609
01:24:47,082 --> 01:24:48,615
Have a seat, please.

1610
01:24:59,761 --> 01:25:03,263
So, I had a call.

1611
01:25:03,598 --> 01:25:05,766
Oh, yes?

1612
01:25:05,768 --> 01:25:10,237
From Richard Bolton,
class of '81.

1613
01:25:11,106 --> 01:25:13,173
Father of Jesse Bolton.

1614
01:25:13,175 --> 01:25:15,375
Do you recall
Jesse Bolton,

1615
01:25:15,377 --> 01:25:17,778
budding journalist,
writes for  <i>The Boston Globe?</i>

1616
01:25:17,780 --> 01:25:19,680
Is this coming back?
Mmm-hmm.

1617
01:25:19,682 --> 01:25:22,749
I remember Jesse Bolton.
We loved Jesse Bolton.

1618
01:25:22,751 --> 01:25:24,384
We accepted Jesse Bolton.

1619
01:25:24,386 --> 01:25:25,619
And yet...

1620
01:25:25,621 --> 01:25:27,287
Mmm.

1621
01:25:29,691 --> 01:25:31,792
So I asked
for the admit list.

1622
01:25:31,794 --> 01:25:35,896
Looked for Bolton, Jesse.
No Bolton, Jesse.

1623
01:25:35,898 --> 01:25:38,632
But I did find
Balakian, Jeremiah.

1624
01:25:41,536 --> 01:25:45,806
We sent Mr. Balakian
an offer of admission,
which he accepted.

1625
01:25:45,808 --> 01:25:47,541
The only thing is,
I don't remember

1626
01:25:47,543 --> 01:25:49,843
making him an
offer of admission.

1627
01:25:49,845 --> 01:25:53,747
But I do remember
your plea that we do so.

1628
01:25:53,749 --> 01:25:57,618
You have exposed
this office
and the university

1629
01:25:57,620 --> 01:26:00,420
to a completely
undeserved scandal.

1630
01:26:00,422 --> 01:26:02,389
If word of this
were ever to get out,

1631
01:26:02,391 --> 01:26:05,159
the damage would
be irreparable.

1632
01:26:06,361 --> 01:26:08,428
Well, I won't tell anyone.

1633
01:26:09,564 --> 01:26:11,832
That's right.
You won't.

1634
01:26:12,934 --> 01:26:15,502
What you will do
is submit your resignation

1635
01:26:15,504 --> 01:26:19,506
and take this week
to clear up your affairs,

1636
01:26:19,508 --> 01:26:23,477
and then I don't
ever want to see you
in this building again.

1637
01:26:32,687 --> 01:26:33,854
He's going to Yale.

1638
01:26:34,889 --> 01:26:37,424
Jesse Bolton.

1639
01:26:37,426 --> 01:26:39,660
The guidance
counselor called me.
We never had a shot at him.

1640
01:26:39,662 --> 01:26:41,895
Yale?

1641
01:26:41,897 --> 01:26:43,597
Well, that's
not the point.

1642
01:26:43,599 --> 01:26:46,200
I assume
you'll be standing
by the offer.

1643
01:26:46,202 --> 01:26:47,935
I don't see
how we can
rescind it without

1644
01:26:47,937 --> 01:26:50,604
the whole thing
blowing up in our faces.

1645
01:26:50,606 --> 01:26:52,339
The whole system
would be questioned.

1646
01:26:53,575 --> 01:26:54,908
We wouldn't want
that to happen.

1647
01:27:01,849 --> 01:27:04,218
(UPBEAT MUSIC PLAYING)

1648
01:27:13,995 --> 01:27:15,529
(KNOCKING)
JOHN: Yeah?

1649
01:27:17,799 --> 01:27:20,300
Oh, hi.
Glad you're here.

1650
01:27:21,502 --> 01:27:23,303
I was just coming
down to the dance.

1651
01:27:23,871 --> 01:27:25,305
(LOCK CLICKS)

1652
01:27:30,378 --> 01:27:32,246
Um, you okay?
Yeah. Why?

1653
01:27:32,248 --> 01:27:33,313
You just...
You seem kind of intense.

1654
01:27:33,315 --> 01:27:34,414
I'm okay.
Are you okay?

1655
01:27:34,416 --> 01:27:35,816
Yeah, I'm great!

1656
01:27:37,719 --> 01:27:39,953
I'm supposed
to be chaperoning
this dance.

1657
01:27:39,955 --> 01:27:41,822
You're doing a great job.

1658
01:27:49,931 --> 01:27:52,466
(MUSIC PLAYING)

1659
01:27:59,774 --> 01:28:01,275
You can do this.

1660
01:28:12,787 --> 01:28:13,920
You having fun?

1661
01:28:15,590 --> 01:28:17,858
This is
the best day
of my life.

1662
01:28:17,860 --> 01:28:21,395
You have no idea
how happy that
makes me feel.

1663
01:28:21,397 --> 01:28:23,930
I want so much
for you to be happy,

1664
01:28:23,932 --> 01:28:26,833
and for you to have
all the things
that you want in life.

1665
01:28:27,535 --> 01:28:28,602
Thanks!

1666
01:28:30,505 --> 01:28:31,872
You know how
when you're swinging

1667
01:28:31,874 --> 01:28:33,607
on a rope swing
across a stream

1668
01:28:33,609 --> 01:28:35,442
and you're afraid to jump in,
and then you just do?

1669
01:28:35,444 --> 01:28:37,577
No. I'm kind
of afraid of heights.

1670
01:28:38,413 --> 01:28:40,480
